{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The flgH, flgI and fliF genes of Salmonella typhimurium encode the major proteins for the L, P and M rings of the flagellar basal body [[cite:PUB00002086]]. In fact, the basal body consists of four rings (L,P,S and M) surrounding the flagellar rod, which is believed to transmit motor rotation to the filament [[cite:PUB00003254]]. The M ring is integral to the inner membrane of the cell, and may be connected to the rod via the S (supramembrane) ring, which lies just distal to it. The L and P rings reside in the outer membrane and periplasmic space, respectively.</p>\r\n<p>The sequences of the FlgH, FlgI and FliF gene products have been determined [[cite:PUB00002086]]. FlgH and FlgI, which are exported across the cell membrane to their destinations in the outer membrane and periplasmic space, have typical N-terminal cleaved signal-peptide sequences [[cite:PUB00002086], [cite:PUB00002059]]. FlgH is predicted to have an extensive β-sheet structure, in keeping with other outer membrane proteins, and FlgI is thought to have even more β-structure content [[cite:PUB00002086]]. Several aspects of the DNA sequence of these genes and their surrounds suggest complex regulation of the flagellar gene system.</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR30381" "FLAGELLAR P-RING PERIPLASMIC PROTEIN FLGI"}, "hamap" {"MF_00416" "Flagellar P-ring protein [flgI]"}, "pfam" {"PF02119" "Flagellar P-ring protein"}, "prints" {"PR01010" "FLGPRINGFLGI"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Flagellar P-ring protein", "short" "Flag_FlgI"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 12, "domain_architectures" 36, "proteomes" 3110, "taxa" 13389, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 16597, "sets" 0, "proteins" 16521, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 12715}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :